WEBVTT

00:04.656 --> 00:05.005
.

00:05.048 --> 00:07.311
- Previously on
"New Amsterdam."

00:07.355 --> 00:08.530
- I see now why they created
a fifth spot for you.

00:08.573 --> 00:09.792
You know the last time
that happened,

00:09.835 --> 00:11.185
Dr Nottingham's family
had to donate

00:11.228 --> 00:12.751
a whole building
to the hospital?

00:12.795 --> 00:14.840
- And I'm sorry

00:14.884 --> 00:17.408
for caring so much about

00:17.452 --> 00:19.323
both of you.

00:19.367 --> 00:22.152
- I know how difficult it was
for you to sign that budget.

00:22.196 --> 00:24.328
These people are
not your friends, Max.

00:24.372 --> 00:26.287
They're your employees.

00:26.330 --> 00:30.117
Believe it or not, you did what
was best for this hospital.

00:30.160 --> 00:31.466
- Today I protected you,

00:31.509 --> 00:35.122
but I can't protect you
tomorrow.

00:36.732 --> 00:38.429
[warm acoustic music]

00:38.473 --> 00:39.822
Goodbye.

00:39.865 --> 00:41.650
- Don't most people start
the day with good morning?

00:41.693 --> 00:44.566
- Yeah, but today is
no ordinary day, Sandra Fall.

00:44.609 --> 00:46.742
Today is my last day.

00:46.785 --> 00:50.528
- Well, since this is our big,
emotional farewell--six feet.

00:50.572 --> 00:51.660
- Sorry.

00:51.703 --> 00:53.357
- You can call me Sandra.
- Oh, wow.

00:53.401 --> 00:56.360
That means a lot
coming from you.

00:56.404 --> 00:58.145
So listen, I wanted
to thank you

00:58.188 --> 01:00.669
for all your hard work
and your hot lists,

01:00.712 --> 01:03.672
and me running you
all over this hospital

01:03.715 --> 01:05.326
to give me information you
could've

01:05.369 --> 01:06.849
just as easily given me
from your office.

01:06.892 --> 01:08.372
- Okay.
- So excuse me,

01:08.416 --> 01:10.157
I'm just going to grab
a quick something.

01:10.200 --> 01:14.857
I got you this little gift,
and by little--

01:14.900 --> 01:16.467
- ♪ Sweetpea

01:16.511 --> 01:20.167
♪ What's all of this about

01:20.210 --> 01:22.604
- Please don't tell me
your cat died.

01:22.647 --> 01:26.390
It's a first edition--rare,
first edition of "Gitanjali"

01:26.434 --> 01:28.218
by Rabindranath Tagore.

01:28.262 --> 01:29.567
Remember Vijay
used to have the book?

01:29.611 --> 01:31.221
He would read you poems
from it,

01:31.265 --> 01:34.485
and sometimes you'd kind of
get a little teared up.

01:34.529 --> 01:36.574
- Look at that.

01:36.618 --> 01:40.230
Interesting.
Mm-hmm.

01:40.274 --> 01:44.930
♪

01:44.974 --> 01:47.716
- Peter Lugar's
steak dinner spectacular

01:47.759 --> 01:49.587
for two
with all the fixings.

01:49.631 --> 01:51.546
- Yeah, I know it's one
of your favorite restaurants,

01:51.589 --> 01:54.505
and I do have to say because
I care about your health

01:54.549 --> 01:55.898
and the sustainability
of the planet,

01:55.941 --> 01:57.769
not to mention the cruel
treatment of animals--

01:57.813 --> 01:59.641
- I'm a vegetarian now.

01:59.684 --> 02:03.253
- Oh, great.

02:03.297 --> 02:05.603
Oh, but then this is--

02:05.647 --> 02:07.649
- Very kind.

02:07.692 --> 02:09.607
- Very thoughtful.

02:09.651 --> 02:11.305
- Your heart was
in the right place.

02:11.348 --> 02:13.611
♪

02:13.655 --> 02:16.788
- Now that stethoscope
belonged to

02:16.832 --> 02:18.703
Vivien Thomas,
one of your heroes,

02:18.747 --> 02:20.836
who used that stethoscope

02:20.879 --> 02:24.840
to help pioneer
modern day heart surgery.

02:24.883 --> 02:27.843
♪

02:29.410 --> 02:30.715
- Appreciate it.

02:30.759 --> 02:33.675
- Appreciate it?
What is with everybody today?

02:33.718 --> 02:35.242
Why is everybody so--

02:35.285 --> 02:36.721
- Disappointed?
- Yeah.

02:36.765 --> 02:39.420
I'm just trying to do
something nice for the people

02:39.463 --> 02:41.204
that I love the most
in the place

02:41.248 --> 02:43.641
that I love the most
one last time.

02:43.685 --> 02:45.643
- Max, look, I'm going
to level with you.

02:45.687 --> 02:48.385
The gift is beyond beautiful.

02:48.429 --> 02:51.780
- So?
- It's just that the only gift

02:51.823 --> 02:54.435
that anyone really wants

02:54.478 --> 02:56.698
is for you to stay.

02:56.741 --> 02:59.701
[somber music]

02:59.744 --> 03:01.964
♪

03:02.007 --> 03:04.706
- Yeah.

03:04.749 --> 03:10.668
♪

03:10.712 --> 03:12.627
- [sighs]
Hi--Trevor Vaughan?

03:12.670 --> 03:14.585
- Reporting for duty,
hopefully.

03:14.629 --> 03:16.370
- Right, right.

03:16.413 --> 03:18.502
I am so sorry that I kept you
waiting like this.

03:18.546 --> 03:20.852
It's not my style,
but my organization

03:20.896 --> 03:22.506
and my scheduling in general

03:22.550 --> 03:24.856
has gone off the rails
since I lost my head nurse.

03:24.900 --> 03:26.815
- No problem at all.
I kept myself busy.

03:26.858 --> 03:29.861
I hope you don't mind,
I saw this on your desk.

03:29.905 --> 03:31.689
- The--oh, yeah/
[laughs]

03:31.733 --> 03:33.604
Yeah, the entire department's
a little fanatical

03:33.648 --> 03:35.084
about the caption contest.

03:35.127 --> 03:37.391
You got any brilliant ideas
I can pass off as my own?

03:37.434 --> 03:38.870
- Hope this isn't
a deal breaker,

03:38.914 --> 03:41.569
but witty captions
are outside of my skill set.

03:41.612 --> 03:43.135
- Drats, Trevor Vaughan.

03:43.179 --> 03:44.789
- Now if you want to talk
keeping behavioral health wards

03:44.833 --> 03:47.618
from going off the rails,
though, I'm your guy.

03:47.662 --> 03:50.404
- Okay, good, let's talk.
All right.

03:50.447 --> 03:51.927
Trained at St. Vincent's
Hospital in Melbourne.

03:51.970 --> 03:53.842
Rose up the ranks at Tufts.

03:53.885 --> 03:55.365
Managed behavioral health
at Baptist.

03:55.409 --> 03:56.932
Trevor,
this is really impressive.

03:56.975 --> 03:58.412
- Thank you.
- Yeah, so I guess

03:58.455 --> 03:59.717
the biggest question
I have right off the bat

03:59.761 --> 04:01.632
is you come
from private institutions.

04:01.676 --> 04:03.112
Do you foresee any problems

04:03.155 --> 04:05.897
working in a public hospital
system like New Amsterdam?

04:05.941 --> 04:07.899
- The only problem I see having
is getting any work done

04:07.943 --> 04:10.946
while staring into those
amazing blue eyes of yours.

04:12.382 --> 04:15.342
[quirky percussive music]

04:15.385 --> 04:18.040
♪

04:18.083 --> 04:19.955
- Yeah....

04:19.998 --> 04:23.393
Yeah, so--

04:23.437 --> 04:24.655
- He actually said that?

04:24.699 --> 04:26.004
- Oh, he lobbed it at me

04:26.048 --> 04:28.833
like we were
at a rave on Fire Island.

04:28.877 --> 04:31.445
- Was he cute?
- Was he cute?

04:31.488 --> 04:33.664
In a sent from Asgard
kind of way.

04:33.708 --> 04:35.492
Chiseled by the gods
sort of way, you know?

04:35.536 --> 04:37.320
And he totally knows it.
- Oh.

04:37.364 --> 04:38.582
Deadly combo.

04:38.626 --> 04:40.454
- Yeah, well,
it takes one to know one.

04:40.497 --> 04:43.935
- I think we can both agree
that four kids has humbled me.

04:43.979 --> 04:47.330
- [laughs]
Perhaps a touch, my love.

04:47.374 --> 04:48.766
But you know,
you got to hand it to him,

04:48.810 --> 04:50.942
the kind of confidence
it takes to go all kamikaze

04:50.986 --> 04:52.988
with the moves
in a job interview?

04:53.031 --> 04:55.033
- It's just completely
unprofessional.

04:55.077 --> 04:57.079
- Oh, oh, yeah, completely.

04:57.122 --> 04:59.734
Completely, no doubt.

04:59.777 --> 05:01.823
Although he just so
happens to be

05:01.866 --> 05:03.259
the best candidate I can afford

05:03.303 --> 05:04.826
under Veronica's new budget
cuts--I'm just saying.

05:04.869 --> 05:06.741
- Yeah, well, I'm sorry
you have to keep looking, babe.

05:06.784 --> 05:09.004
- Yeah, I know.
Me too.

05:09.047 --> 05:10.962
You know, I've got to say that
the whole thing has left me

05:11.006 --> 05:12.877
feeling kind of charged,
like the thrill of it

05:12.921 --> 05:15.097
left me feeling great,

05:15.140 --> 05:17.012
if not a touch guilty.

05:17.055 --> 05:20.058
- Iggy, don't feel guilty.

05:20.102 --> 05:22.539
Your eyes are gorgeous.

05:22.583 --> 05:23.671
- Thank you, husband.

05:23.714 --> 05:24.933
- You'll find someone.

05:24.976 --> 05:28.023
- I know, I know.

05:28.066 --> 05:30.591
- Dr. Malvo, wait up.

05:30.634 --> 05:32.984
Whew, man, you are a hard woman
to catch-up to.

05:33.028 --> 05:34.464
- I did do the 400
in high school.

05:34.508 --> 05:35.639
- Yeah, I can see that,

05:35.683 --> 05:37.119
but can you just stop
for one moment?

05:37.162 --> 05:39.469
- That's generally not
how one wins a race.

05:39.513 --> 05:41.819
- Look, I've been texting you
and leaving you messages.

05:41.863 --> 05:43.473
And can you just talk to me?

05:43.517 --> 05:45.083
- I know you want to apologize
and say you had nothing to do

05:45.127 --> 05:46.781
with Claude getting the axe.
I believe you,

05:46.824 --> 05:48.826
you're not vindictive.
That's not how you roll.

05:48.870 --> 05:50.611
- Okay, but look, what happened
to Claude was messed up.

05:50.654 --> 05:54.702
But, hey, we've been through
too much to just end it.

05:54.745 --> 05:57.705
[somber music]

05:57.748 --> 06:04.755
♪

06:06.453 --> 06:08.411
- But it's just--it's, um--

06:08.455 --> 06:11.936
it's too complicated now.

06:15.026 --> 06:17.855
I'm sorry.

06:17.899 --> 06:20.597
♪

06:20.641 --> 06:23.600
[indistinct
P.A. announcements]

06:23.644 --> 06:30.172
♪

06:30.215 --> 06:33.218
- I know that we stopped
eating meat and fish,

06:33.262 --> 06:35.830
but what do you say to

06:35.873 --> 06:38.659
20 side orders of spinach?

06:40.269 --> 06:41.705
- How much did you spend?

06:41.749 --> 06:43.533
- Oh, that's the best part.

06:43.577 --> 06:46.057
Zero dollars, a gift from Max.

06:46.101 --> 06:47.537
- No.

06:47.581 --> 06:50.888
How much did you spend
to buy my residency?

06:52.499 --> 06:54.501
[soft tense music]

06:54.544 --> 06:55.850
- Where did you hear that?

06:55.893 --> 06:59.070
- Answer the question.
How big was your bribe?

06:59.114 --> 07:01.638
A- I didn't bribe.
I didn't bribe anyone.

07:01.682 --> 07:04.467
♪

07:04.511 --> 07:07.470
I didn't, I...

07:07.514 --> 07:10.995
All I did--all I did was
make a donation.

07:11.039 --> 07:13.041
- A donation that happened
to get your girlfriend

07:13.084 --> 07:16.610
a non-existent residency
at New Amsterdam?

07:16.653 --> 07:18.786
- Come on, we both know
it's a joke that you had

07:18.829 --> 07:21.658
to do your residency at all,

07:21.702 --> 07:24.922
but when the dean saw
an application from a doctor

07:24.966 --> 07:26.750
who trained in Pakistan

07:26.794 --> 07:30.754
at a hospital he never
heard of, he stopped reading.

07:30.798 --> 07:32.669
I mean, you could
have cured cancer

07:32.713 --> 07:34.149
and you wouldn't have
gotten that spot.

07:34.192 --> 07:37.500
All I did--all I did was
open up the dean's eyes

07:37.544 --> 07:39.850
to see that--that you were
the best candidate.

07:39.894 --> 07:42.853
- How much?

07:42.897 --> 07:48.859
♪

07:48.903 --> 07:50.861
- $90,000.

07:50.905 --> 07:52.776
♪

07:52.820 --> 07:57.172
Leyla, I did this for you.

07:57.215 --> 08:00.567
For us.

08:00.610 --> 08:02.786
- Oh, hey, guys.
Hi, I'm glad I caught you.

08:02.830 --> 08:04.135
Um, did you guys hear about
the blue-eyed hottie

08:04.179 --> 08:06.181
that got hit on today
in the psych ward?

08:06.224 --> 08:08.226
Did you?
Did news reach the ED?

08:08.270 --> 08:10.228
It was me!

08:10.272 --> 08:17.279
♪

08:23.111 --> 08:24.678
- Well, did they
love your gifts?

08:24.721 --> 08:27.071
- Oh, yeah, they--
they loved them.

08:27.115 --> 08:30.292
If by love, you mean
dispassionate indifference

08:30.335 --> 08:32.642
couched
in a thinly veiled apathy,

08:32.686 --> 08:34.775
with just a hint of anger.
- [laughs]

08:34.818 --> 08:38.648
Go easy on them.
It's hard to say goodbye.

08:38.692 --> 08:40.171
- You seem cool as a cucumber.

08:40.215 --> 08:42.565
- I am going to miss
this place, you know I am,

08:42.609 --> 08:45.568
but we are getting ready
for a brand new chapter

08:45.612 --> 08:47.657
of our lives
together in London.

08:47.701 --> 08:49.746
Tell me you're not excited
about that?

08:49.790 --> 08:52.270
- I'm excited, I am excited.

08:52.314 --> 08:55.056
- [sighs]
Good.

08:55.099 --> 08:57.275
Okay, so Luna's all settled
for a week in Connecticut

08:57.319 --> 08:58.712
with Glenn and Calvin?
- Check.

08:58.755 --> 08:59.887
- We have handed over the keys
to the subletter?

08:59.930 --> 09:01.018
- Check.

09:01.062 --> 09:02.672
- We've checked in
for our flight?

09:02.716 --> 09:04.282
- Check and check.

09:04.326 --> 09:06.763
- Well, then it's time to go.

09:06.807 --> 09:10.027
[gentle music]

09:10.071 --> 09:12.029
♪

09:12.073 --> 09:15.032
- It doesn't feel real,
does it?

09:15.076 --> 09:18.079
♪

09:18.122 --> 09:19.820
- Come on.

09:19.863 --> 09:22.344
♪

09:22.387 --> 09:24.607
[pager beeping]

09:24.651 --> 09:25.956
- Sorry, uncheck.

09:26.000 --> 09:28.219
Pager.
Forgot to return it.

09:28.263 --> 09:30.613
- Max.
- I'll be right back.

09:30.657 --> 09:32.354
[beeping continues]

09:32.397 --> 09:34.356
- BP dropping, 60 over 20.

09:34.399 --> 09:37.098
Septic shock, hypotension.
We're losing him here.

09:37.141 --> 09:38.839
- Patient came in for
a routine cardiac stent.

09:38.882 --> 09:40.275
What the hell happened?

09:40.318 --> 09:42.625
[pager continues beeping]
- Yeah, that makes sense.

09:42.669 --> 09:44.627
That's why we try to reframe
these feelings of anger,

09:44.671 --> 09:46.934
you know?
New context--Kaelen.

09:46.977 --> 09:48.152
Hey, what's the matter?
- [groans]

09:48.196 --> 09:49.371
- Kaelen?

09:49.414 --> 09:50.807
Kaelen, Kaelen--
okay, you're okay.

09:50.851 --> 09:53.810
You're okay, you're okay.
Ka--help, help!

09:53.854 --> 09:56.726
I need some help.

09:56.770 --> 09:59.381
No pulse.
No pulse, call a code team now.

09:59.424 --> 10:00.991
[pager continues beeping]

10:01.035 --> 10:03.124
[tense dramatic music]

10:03.167 --> 10:05.648
- What is it?
- Clear.

10:05.692 --> 10:07.998
♪

10:08.042 --> 10:09.217
- Still no pulse.

10:09.260 --> 10:12.742
- Going again.
- Charging.

10:12.786 --> 10:15.179
- Clear.

10:15.223 --> 10:17.965
Nothing.
- What the hell just happened?

10:18.008 --> 10:19.836
- We just had nine code blues
at the same time.

10:19.880 --> 10:21.882
♪

10:21.925 --> 10:24.275
- How is that possible?

10:24.319 --> 10:27.322
[machines emitting flat tone]

10:32.414 --> 10:32.588
.

10:32.632 --> 10:34.459
- We need to shut down
the hospital.

10:34.503 --> 10:36.418
[overlapping chatter]

10:36.461 --> 10:38.246
- Bam.
Dead, in the hallway.

10:38.289 --> 10:41.075
- All right.
Everyone listen up.

10:41.118 --> 10:43.251
I've alerted Veronica,
but she's still in Chicago,

10:43.294 --> 10:45.557
so this is on us,
and here are the facts.

10:45.601 --> 10:47.385
Nine patients died
this morning.

10:47.429 --> 10:49.561
They were all colonized
by a bacterium infection,

10:49.605 --> 10:52.042
Klebsiella Pneumoniae
Carbapenemase.

10:52.086 --> 10:53.653
- I'm sorry, but what is that?

10:53.696 --> 10:56.264
- A superbug that's resistant
to most of our antibiotics.

10:56.307 --> 10:58.440
- Ah.
- Now the good news is

10:58.483 --> 11:01.661
KPC isn't airborne
like a virus or COVID.

11:01.704 --> 11:04.054
It's spread by direct contact
through an open wound

11:04.098 --> 11:06.187
or ingestion,
but that's the only good news.

11:06.230 --> 11:08.276
From there, the bacteria
quickly spreads to the lungs,

11:08.319 --> 11:11.061
where our patient's died
of either bacterial pneumonia

11:11.105 --> 11:12.410
or pulmonary embolism.

11:12.454 --> 11:13.977
- Where are they
all getting it from?

11:14.021 --> 11:14.978
- Well, all the infections came

11:15.022 --> 11:16.284
from different departments.

11:16.327 --> 11:17.546
I mean, it could be anywhere
in the hospital.

11:17.589 --> 11:21.245
- Ten more patients
just tested positive.

11:21.289 --> 11:22.594
- So what do we do now?

11:22.638 --> 11:24.205
- Well, we have
to call the NIH.

11:24.248 --> 11:25.685
I mean, this could be
in other hospitals.

11:25.728 --> 11:29.601
[overlapping chatter]

11:29.645 --> 11:31.429
- Hey!

11:31.473 --> 11:33.214
I'll call the top people
at the CDC.

11:33.257 --> 11:34.998
We'll get their infection
control team here,

11:35.042 --> 11:36.565
we'll find a treatment
for the infected,

11:36.608 --> 11:39.089
Dr. Sharpe can conduct
a hospital-wide search

11:39.133 --> 11:40.134
for the source.

11:40.177 --> 11:41.613
- Max, you've got
a plane to catch.

11:41.657 --> 11:42.832
- I know, but there's no way

11:42.876 --> 11:44.573
I'm going to leave
this hospital in crisis.

11:44.616 --> 11:47.184
- Absolutely,
this is more important.

11:47.228 --> 11:49.970
♪

11:55.671 --> 11:59.022
- There's no easy way to say
what I'm about to say.

12:02.547 --> 12:05.028
Your son...

12:05.072 --> 12:06.769
- Was there
another manic episode?

12:06.813 --> 12:09.511
- No, it's not that.
- Where's our son, doctor?

12:11.556 --> 12:15.299
- Your son contracted
a bacterial infection

12:15.343 --> 12:18.302
here at the hospital, and...

12:18.346 --> 12:20.783
[somber music]

12:20.827 --> 12:25.179
He passed away.

12:25.222 --> 12:27.703
I am so sorry.

12:27.747 --> 12:31.228
- Okay, are
the cameras in here?

12:31.272 --> 12:32.795
- Excuse me?

12:32.839 --> 12:34.188
- I don't know how much
you know about our son, doctor.

12:34.231 --> 12:35.624
Maybe you're part of this?

12:35.667 --> 12:38.061
- He pranks us all the time
for that TikTok thing.

12:38.105 --> 12:39.193
He's obsessed.

12:39.236 --> 12:41.630
He's 17.
He gets his friends to help.

12:41.673 --> 12:43.240
- [chuckles]

12:43.284 --> 12:44.676
- No.

12:44.720 --> 12:46.809
No, I-I assure you, I'm not--
- All right.

12:46.853 --> 12:50.117
Maybe you're a part of this,
maybe he's playing you.

12:50.160 --> 12:52.641
I really don't care.
But I want to see him now.

12:52.684 --> 12:55.687
- Mr. and Mrs. Mancini,

12:55.731 --> 12:59.343
I am very sorry,
but your son is dead.

12:59.387 --> 13:02.651
♪

13:02.694 --> 13:04.784
- All right.
Enough fooling around.

13:04.827 --> 13:08.352
I want to see Kaelen now.

13:08.396 --> 13:12.313
♪

13:12.356 --> 13:15.229
[tense music]

13:15.272 --> 13:18.362
- Dr. Goodwin?
Simon Holgate, from CDC.

13:18.406 --> 13:21.365
- Yeah, where is Julie Framm
or Dr. Wu?

13:21.409 --> 13:23.672
Sorry, we just had
a major bacterial outbreak.

13:23.715 --> 13:25.543
We've already lost patients
and our ICU's

13:25.587 --> 13:27.328
completely overwhelmed.
We need the A team here,

13:27.371 --> 13:30.548
and you seem
a little Gen Z-ish.

13:30.592 --> 13:32.463
- Dr. Goodwin,
I started at the CDC

13:32.507 --> 13:34.074
straight out of Johns Hopkins.

13:34.117 --> 13:35.771
I've resolved crises
in Ghana, India,

13:35.815 --> 13:37.599
most recently at the NIH
in Bethesda,

13:37.642 --> 13:39.644
where I identified
the frame shift mutation

13:39.688 --> 13:41.168
in their KPC outbreak.

13:41.211 --> 13:44.780
- Oh.
- I am the A team.

13:44.824 --> 13:46.695
- Alright.
Everyone, listen up.

13:46.738 --> 13:48.740
All non-trauma patients
have been diverted,

13:48.784 --> 13:51.134
but we are still up
and running.

13:51.178 --> 13:53.397
Everything needs to be cleaned
and disinfected.

13:53.441 --> 13:55.225
If in doubt, toss it.

13:55.269 --> 13:58.272
[indistinct chatter]

13:58.315 --> 13:59.708
- Years of medical school,
but they can't make

13:59.751 --> 14:03.320
a decent pot of java
to save their lives.

14:03.364 --> 14:04.582
- What?
- The coffee.

14:04.626 --> 14:05.888
This stuff like's mud.

14:05.932 --> 14:08.238
You got to ice it down
to make it drinkable.

14:08.282 --> 14:09.326
[laughs]

14:09.370 --> 14:10.675
I'm actually
a latte guy myself--

14:10.719 --> 14:12.112
- There is a superbug
infection running rampant

14:12.155 --> 14:13.417
in the hospital,

14:13.461 --> 14:15.245
and you're talking
about coffee.

14:16.812 --> 14:18.118
- Why do I even try?

14:18.161 --> 14:20.424
- Addison Stadler,
24-year-old male.

14:20.468 --> 14:22.122
Un-helmeted
motorcycle accident,

14:22.165 --> 14:23.775
head trauma,
unresponsive in the field.

14:23.819 --> 14:26.604
- Trauma one, Shinwari,
you're with me.

14:26.648 --> 14:28.780
Let's go.
Okay.

14:28.824 --> 14:30.782
♪

14:30.826 --> 14:34.264
Addison, can you hear me?
Addison?

14:34.308 --> 14:36.658
[indistinct chatter,
machinery beeping]

14:36.701 --> 14:38.268
- Pupils are fixed and dilated.

14:38.312 --> 14:40.183
- GCS score of three.

14:42.359 --> 14:43.752
- He's becoming hyperthermic.

14:43.795 --> 14:45.841
- Complete brain stem
dysfunction.

14:45.885 --> 14:48.452
- We've got to keep
his temperature under control.

14:48.496 --> 14:50.933
- Wrap his body in ice and
I'll grab a cooling blanket.

14:50.977 --> 14:53.457
Check his license.
See if he's an organ donor.

14:53.501 --> 14:55.590
He's not coming back from this.

14:55.633 --> 14:59.681
♪

14:59.724 --> 15:02.423
- Lauren?
- How's it going on your end?

15:02.466 --> 15:03.467
Any connection
between the patients?

15:03.511 --> 15:04.729
- None that I can find,

15:04.773 --> 15:06.470
but I need you
to take over the KPC ward.

15:06.514 --> 15:08.516
- How bad?

15:08.559 --> 15:09.821
- It's getting worse
by the minute.

15:09.865 --> 15:12.389
- Okay, go.
I'll head up there now.

15:16.002 --> 15:17.438
- I heard your patient's lungs

15:17.481 --> 15:19.353
are stiff
and difficult to ventilate.

15:19.396 --> 15:22.312
- Yes, and I paged
for a general consult.

15:22.356 --> 15:24.836
The chair of surgery
doesn't need to swoop in.

15:24.880 --> 15:26.577
- If it's a possible
KPC infection,

15:26.621 --> 15:28.492
I need to know about it.
- Okay.

15:28.536 --> 15:30.755
- And, Lyn, you should know

15:30.799 --> 15:32.322
that I'm in for complicated.

15:32.366 --> 15:33.889
And being with you has shown me

15:33.933 --> 15:37.414
that I might even
like complicated.

15:38.285 --> 15:41.201
[rapid beeping]

15:48.556 --> 15:51.298
Course rhonci throughout
with diminished breath sounds.

15:51.341 --> 15:52.995
Left lower lobe.

15:53.039 --> 15:54.866
That's how my last patient
with KPC started.

15:54.910 --> 15:56.390
- X-ray tells the same story.
- All right.

15:56.433 --> 15:57.739
Well, there's no treatment
for this,

15:57.782 --> 15:59.306
but if we can remove
the infected lobe

15:59.349 --> 16:00.785
before it spreads
to the rest of the lungs,

16:00.829 --> 16:02.483
we might be able to stop
the infection in its tracks.

16:02.526 --> 16:04.964
- That's a long shot.
- It's all we got.

16:05.007 --> 16:08.010
♪

16:08.054 --> 16:10.230
- Simon,
tell me you got good news.

16:10.273 --> 16:12.841
- I put the CDC's strongest
antibiotics in each dish--

16:12.884 --> 16:14.886
Cipro, Colistin, Vancomycin.

16:14.930 --> 16:17.019
Bacteria should not be able
to survive in this environment.

16:17.063 --> 16:18.020
- And?

16:18.064 --> 16:19.717
- New Amsterdam's KPC strain

16:19.761 --> 16:21.850
not only survived,
it flourished.

16:21.893 --> 16:23.547
- Nothing worked?

16:23.591 --> 16:25.941
- This is what antibiotic
resistance looks like.

16:25.985 --> 16:28.596
New Amsterdam is
the third hospital this year

16:28.639 --> 16:31.555
to get an infection like this.

16:31.599 --> 16:35.385
- And what happened to patients
at the other hospitals?

16:35.429 --> 16:38.345
- They died.

16:44.568 --> 16:44.742
.

16:44.786 --> 16:46.918
- There must be a common link,

16:46.962 --> 16:49.660
but all the infected
came from different floors.

16:49.704 --> 16:51.445
They were admitted
to different departments,

16:51.488 --> 16:53.273
and given various treatments.

16:53.316 --> 16:56.624
- From arrival
to first symptoms,

16:56.667 --> 16:58.974
looks like roughly a 48-hour
incubation period

16:59.018 --> 17:01.498
for the bacteria.
- Okay.

17:01.542 --> 17:04.197
So...

17:04.240 --> 17:07.417
let's go back
to hour one for every patient.

17:07.461 --> 17:09.593
Where did they enter?

17:09.637 --> 17:12.248
- All but three went in
through the ED.

17:12.292 --> 17:13.467
- Okay, then what?

17:13.510 --> 17:15.338
- Six went through radiology
for imaging.

17:15.382 --> 17:17.862
- And five went to cardio.

17:17.906 --> 17:19.603
- Okay, then those
are our common links.

17:19.647 --> 17:21.301
We need to put the ED
on full diversion

17:21.344 --> 17:23.433
and lockdown cardiology
and radiology.

17:23.477 --> 17:25.870
We have to test
every square inch.

17:25.914 --> 17:28.960
- Don't we need the medical
director to authorize that?

17:29.004 --> 17:31.659
- Well, when she returns, you
can tell her to give me a ring.

17:31.702 --> 17:33.617
- Okay, guys, let's go.

17:38.318 --> 17:41.364
- So you're telling me
the strongest antibacterial

17:41.408 --> 17:42.539
the CDC has won't work?

17:42.583 --> 17:44.628
- It doesn't even make a dent.

17:44.672 --> 17:47.283
- Well, then we need to think
of something else, and fast.

17:47.327 --> 17:49.068
Our supplies are pushed
to the brink.

17:49.111 --> 17:51.766
I mean, the ward you just put
me in charge of is almost full.

17:51.809 --> 17:53.637
- Okay, what about something
other than antibiotics,

17:53.681 --> 17:54.899
like phage therapy.

17:54.943 --> 17:56.640
- I've already tried it.

17:56.684 --> 17:58.294
Nothing in the phage trials
works on this train.

17:58.338 --> 18:01.384
- Immunotherapeutics,
like pegfilgrastim?

18:01.428 --> 18:05.084
- Or heavy doses of probiotics
for microbiota modulation?

18:05.127 --> 18:06.868
- They're good as
preventative measures,

18:06.911 --> 18:10.567
but it's too late
to help those already infected.

18:13.004 --> 18:15.746
- What about CRISPR?

18:15.790 --> 18:17.270
We could alter the Cas9 enzyme

18:17.313 --> 18:20.360
and turn the KPC gene function
against itself.

18:20.403 --> 18:21.883
- Possibly.

18:21.926 --> 18:26.583
It's experimental and time
consuming, but it could work.

18:26.627 --> 18:28.455
- Let's do it.

18:28.498 --> 18:30.413
- Can you believe this, Thora?

18:30.457 --> 18:31.980
You believe what this kid
puts us through?

18:32.023 --> 18:33.895
- Don't yell at him.
- I'm not going to yell at him.

18:33.938 --> 18:39.074
He's gonna know I'm over this.
- Okay, okay.

18:39.118 --> 18:41.598
The denial of death,
of our own mortality,

18:41.642 --> 18:45.385
of the mortality of the people
we love, it is essential.

18:45.428 --> 18:48.866
If we were constantly aware
of our own fragility,

18:48.910 --> 18:50.955
of the emptiness
that we are this close

18:50.999 --> 18:53.697
to all the time,
we would be filled with terror.

18:53.741 --> 18:55.308
Right now your brain
is trying to protect you.

18:55.351 --> 18:58.833
I am trying to protect you
from that terror,

18:58.876 --> 19:00.791
but if I open that door
and I show you your son--

19:00.835 --> 19:02.924
- Open the door, doctor.

19:06.841 --> 19:08.408
[somber music]

19:08.451 --> 19:09.931
- Okay.

19:09.974 --> 19:11.933
[door alarm buzzes]

19:11.976 --> 19:18.983
♪

19:40.831 --> 19:46.446
♪

19:46.489 --> 19:48.143
- [whispering]
Oh, my God.

19:48.187 --> 19:53.670
♪

19:53.714 --> 19:57.370
Kaelen?
Kaelen?

19:57.413 --> 20:00.460
♪

20:00.503 --> 20:03.680
Kaelen?
Kaelen?

20:03.724 --> 20:06.161
♪

20:06.205 --> 20:07.989
Kaelen?

20:08.032 --> 20:10.644
♪

20:10.687 --> 20:12.167
[crying]

20:12.211 --> 20:15.388
- Mr. Mancini, I know
the pain you must bein--

20:18.042 --> 20:21.045
- This ward is
KPC patients only.

20:21.089 --> 20:24.571
- That's why we're here.
- Walsh?

20:24.614 --> 20:27.182
- Don't you dare be nice
to me now.

20:27.226 --> 20:30.490
♪

20:30.533 --> 20:32.100
- [sighs]

20:37.497 --> 20:42.676
Walsh hasn't been anywhere
near radiology all week.

20:42.719 --> 20:44.155
- And we've cross-checked
his whereabouts

20:44.199 --> 20:46.201
with all other departments.

20:46.245 --> 20:48.943
- Which leaves us with this.
Here's our epicenter.

20:52.076 --> 20:56.167
- Full resection of the left
KPC-infected lobe complete.

20:56.211 --> 20:58.169
- I see pus on the right lung.

20:58.213 --> 20:59.997
[indistinct chatter]

21:00.041 --> 21:02.565
- Oh, damn it.
That is KPC, all right.

21:02.609 --> 21:04.741
- We can probably
resect the right lobe too.

21:04.785 --> 21:07.135
- Uh...

21:07.178 --> 21:08.571
Won't matter.
It's spread.

21:08.615 --> 21:10.007
It's everywhere.

21:10.051 --> 21:12.445
- So our only option
will be a transplant?

21:12.488 --> 21:14.534
- Yeah, I guess we can
put her on ECMO.

21:14.577 --> 21:16.275
That'll buy her 36 hours
to find a donor.

21:16.318 --> 21:19.147
- And if we don't find one?

21:19.190 --> 21:22.150
[intense music]

21:22.193 --> 21:24.631
♪

21:24.674 --> 21:27.677
[machine emitting flat beep]

21:35.903 --> 21:38.471
- Time of death, 2:14 p.m.

21:38.514 --> 21:41.474
[tense dramatic music]

21:41.517 --> 21:45.739
♪

21:45.782 --> 21:47.523
- I've checked
everyone's results on CRISPR.

21:47.567 --> 21:49.743
- It's not working.
We just lost another one.

21:49.786 --> 21:51.571
- It was immediately degraded
in the body.

21:51.614 --> 21:54.661
- Okay, then we just have
to think of something else.

21:54.704 --> 22:01.711
♪

22:05.628 --> 22:05.846
.

22:05.889 --> 22:07.369
- Test every nook and cranny,

22:07.413 --> 22:08.370
trash can, table,

22:08.414 --> 22:09.545
chair, catheter bag,

22:09.589 --> 22:10.894
stethoscope, suture tray,

22:10.938 --> 22:13.375
and I hate Mondays mugs
in this department.

22:13.419 --> 22:14.855
Something is infecting people

22:14.898 --> 22:17.423
and we've got to find out
what it is.

22:17.466 --> 22:20.426
[tense music]

22:20.469 --> 22:23.429
[indistinct chatter]

22:23.472 --> 22:30.479
♪

22:35.789 --> 22:37.878
- There's too many
possibilities.

22:37.921 --> 22:40.663
I hope you pushed your flight
to next month.

22:40.707 --> 22:43.405
- Well, it'll take
as long as it takes.

22:43.449 --> 22:47.801
♪

22:47.844 --> 22:50.717
[sighs]

22:50.760 --> 22:54.416
- All right, let's try target
signaling and regulation.

22:54.460 --> 22:55.939
- Unless you have
a time machine,

22:55.983 --> 22:57.593
that's theoretical.

22:57.637 --> 23:00.422
- Okay, then we can change
the patient's microbiome,

23:00.466 --> 23:01.858
and we can do
a fecal transplant--

23:01.902 --> 23:03.033
- And risk more infection?

23:03.077 --> 23:04.513
- Then how about you
give me an idea

23:04.557 --> 23:07.777
instead of
just shooting them down.

23:07.821 --> 23:10.606
- I have tested every drug,
modeled every outcome,

23:10.650 --> 23:12.434
and all these roads
lead to the same place.

23:12.478 --> 23:15.437
I'm sorry, Max, but there's
no antibiotics on the market

23:15.481 --> 23:19.093
that can fight this infection.

23:19.136 --> 23:21.617
- That could work.

23:21.661 --> 23:22.749
- Wait, what?

23:22.792 --> 23:24.533
- You're saying test
old antibiotics

23:24.577 --> 23:26.100
that aren't in the market.

23:26.143 --> 23:27.493
- Definitely not
what I'm saying.

23:27.536 --> 23:29.538
- It's brilliant.
- But it's not what I'm saying.

23:29.582 --> 23:31.061
- But it's genius.

23:31.105 --> 23:33.673
- Max, antibiotics get pulled
from the market

23:33.716 --> 23:36.458
for specific reasons--
namely for killing people.

23:36.502 --> 23:39.026
- And I've got over 14 patients
upstairs with a superbug

23:39.069 --> 23:40.462
decimating their bodies,

23:40.506 --> 23:43.987
so I think we're
in hail mary territory.

23:44.031 --> 23:48.078
So please,
can we start testing?

23:50.516 --> 23:53.475
- Okay.

23:53.519 --> 23:54.868
- This isn't our fault.

23:54.911 --> 23:56.652
- No, I know.
No one is saying it is.

23:56.696 --> 23:58.437
- Yeah, but how could he
be here one minute,

23:58.480 --> 24:00.743
and just--
the next minute, he's--

24:00.787 --> 24:04.138
- Our son is dead.

24:04.181 --> 24:05.661
- You know what, Dora,
let's go.

24:05.705 --> 24:06.836
We don't have to stay here.

24:06.880 --> 24:09.752
- Our baby is dead, Dominic.

24:09.796 --> 24:12.189
I'm not going back
into that house.

24:12.233 --> 24:14.583
[somber music]

24:14.627 --> 24:17.847
That emptiness.

24:17.891 --> 24:20.023
- We can find you
somewhere quiet to grieve here.

24:20.067 --> 24:21.503
- What, in this hospital?

24:21.547 --> 24:23.157
This place that killed my boy?

24:23.200 --> 24:25.072
♪

24:25.115 --> 24:28.858
- This isn't the hospital's
fault, Dominic.

24:28.902 --> 24:30.033
It's yours.

24:30.077 --> 24:32.514
Kaelen was never good enough
for him.

24:32.558 --> 24:35.517
He never gave that boy an inch,
so of course he acted out,

24:35.561 --> 24:36.953
and ended up in here.

24:36.997 --> 24:38.564
- Yeah, yeah, listen to this.

24:38.607 --> 24:40.174
Perfect mama's boy,
could never do anything wrong.

24:40.217 --> 24:42.698
You know, I saw this
coming for years,

24:42.742 --> 24:44.091
but she would
never listen to me.

24:44.134 --> 24:45.527
All she could do
is protect him.

24:45.571 --> 24:46.963
- You screamed at him
every day.

24:47.007 --> 24:48.835
- I did not scream--
- No, stop!

24:48.878 --> 24:50.706
You can't--
you cannot blame each other.

24:50.750 --> 24:52.534
♪

24:52.578 --> 24:55.058
- All she ever did
was blame me, always.

24:56.495 --> 24:57.887
- [sobbing]

24:57.931 --> 24:59.846
Oh, Kaelen.

24:59.889 --> 25:02.457
God...

25:02.501 --> 25:06.200
♪

25:06.243 --> 25:08.768
Kaelen.

25:21.563 --> 25:25.611
Without our little boy,

25:25.654 --> 25:28.527
what do we have?

25:28.570 --> 25:35.534
♪

25:38.841 --> 25:41.801
[machinery beeping]

25:41.844 --> 25:44.804
[soft dramatic music]

25:44.847 --> 25:51.854
♪

26:02.996 --> 26:04.127
- They're sick because of us.

26:04.171 --> 26:07.043
- Don't.
This is a hospital.

26:07.087 --> 26:09.263
Some people get better.
Some get worse.

26:09.306 --> 26:12.701
- Yeah, but ideally we're
not the ones making it worse.

26:15.922 --> 26:19.621
My sister died here.

26:19.665 --> 26:23.146
From an infection
just like this.

26:23.190 --> 26:26.628
- I remember you telling us
that on your first day.

26:26.672 --> 26:29.326
- All the doctor
said to me was,

26:29.370 --> 26:32.895
"I'm sorry,
there's nothing we can do."

26:32.939 --> 26:36.595
I felt helpless.

26:38.335 --> 26:39.728
How can I leave this hospital

26:39.772 --> 26:42.557
when it's happening
all over again?

26:43.776 --> 26:46.039
- Then don't.

26:53.829 --> 26:56.789
[somber music]

26:56.832 --> 26:58.181
♪

26:58.225 --> 27:02.011
- Guys, I know you're all
exhausted and frustrated,

27:02.055 --> 27:07.016
but people are--
are counting on us.

27:07.060 --> 27:10.019
Walsh is counting on us.

27:10.063 --> 27:13.283
♪

27:13.327 --> 27:16.156
Okay, look, everybody,
take a coffee break.

27:16.199 --> 27:18.245
That might help give us
a second wind.

27:18.288 --> 27:20.856
- The iceman cometh.

27:20.900 --> 27:22.292
- What does that mean?

27:22.336 --> 27:24.251
- Oh, it's just an inside joke

27:24.294 --> 27:27.646
all the residents
have with Walsh.

27:27.689 --> 27:29.256
- We nicknamed Walsh
the iceman

27:29.299 --> 27:32.215
because he always complains
that our coffee is too strong.

27:32.259 --> 27:34.609
He always has to dump
a ton of ice in his mug

27:34.653 --> 27:37.177
to water it down.

27:37.220 --> 27:39.919
Drives him crazy.
- [chuckles]

27:39.962 --> 27:46.055
♪

27:46.099 --> 27:49.058
[music intensifies]

27:49.102 --> 27:53.367
♪

27:53.410 --> 27:55.674
- How old is this ice machine?

27:55.717 --> 27:58.372
- It's older than all of you.

27:58.415 --> 28:01.375
[machine whirring]

28:01.418 --> 28:08.208
♪

28:08.251 --> 28:11.646
Swab?
Thank you.

28:19.132 --> 28:21.134
[device chirps]

28:21.177 --> 28:24.746
We found our infection point.

28:24.790 --> 28:27.053
Now what else was
this machine used for?

28:27.096 --> 28:29.229
- I hate feeling lucky.
- Well, our patient is lucky

28:29.272 --> 28:30.926
that Mr. Stadler
was an organ donor.

28:30.970 --> 28:32.449
You and I can feel grateful.

28:32.493 --> 28:35.235
- Transplant team ready?
- Yeah, they're coming in now.

28:35.278 --> 28:38.194
They'll harvest both lungs
to give Maru the best shot.

28:38.238 --> 28:39.761
- Stop!

28:39.805 --> 28:42.024
Is that Addison Stadler,
motorcycle MDA?

28:42.068 --> 28:43.809
- Yeah, are you assisting
with the transplant?

28:43.852 --> 28:45.680
- You need to call it off.
- Why?

28:45.724 --> 28:47.769
- That patient's lungs were
exposed to the KPC bacteria.

28:47.813 --> 28:48.944
- No.
- The ED wrapped him in ice

28:48.988 --> 28:50.032
to control
his body temperature.

28:50.076 --> 28:52.208
That ice harbors the bacteria.

28:52.252 --> 28:54.863
- My patient needs these lungs.
She only has hours left.

28:54.907 --> 28:57.170
- I understand that,
but you can't use these.

28:57.213 --> 29:00.129
They'll be a death sentence.

29:00.173 --> 29:03.176
♪

29:03.219 --> 29:07.049
- [coughing]

29:15.362 --> 29:16.798
- We've got something,

29:16.842 --> 29:20.454
an antibacterial solution
that worked against the KPC.

29:20.497 --> 29:22.325
- See?
What did I tell you?

29:22.369 --> 29:24.371
Hospital spent way
too much money training you.

29:24.414 --> 29:26.765
No way we're
gonna let you die.

29:26.808 --> 29:30.899
- Your bedside manner
is a thing to behold.

29:33.946 --> 29:35.817
- So what's the drug?

29:35.861 --> 29:39.386
- Tolomycin.
- From the 1950s?

29:39.429 --> 29:40.779
Wasn't that taken
off the shelves

29:40.822 --> 29:42.302
because it decimated
people's kidneys?

29:42.345 --> 29:45.218
- Technically yes,
but as we give people the drug,

29:45.261 --> 29:47.002
we'll simultaneously
administer dialysis.

29:47.046 --> 29:48.525
- So we keep them alive

29:48.569 --> 29:50.397
but we risk destroying
their renal systems?

29:50.440 --> 29:51.920
Is that really
our best solution?

29:51.964 --> 29:53.748
- At the moment,
it's our only solution.

29:53.792 --> 29:55.532
- We're not quite ready
to press go.

29:55.576 --> 29:56.969
We haven't tried it
on a patient yet.

29:57.012 --> 29:59.275
- I should hope not.

29:59.319 --> 30:02.148
- Try it on me.

30:03.889 --> 30:06.848
[somber music]

30:06.892 --> 30:13.899
♪

30:43.929 --> 30:50.936
♪

31:20.966 --> 31:27.973
♪

31:38.157 --> 31:41.029
